function binary_search(arr, target) {
  let first = 0;
  let last = arr.length - 1;

  while (first <= last) {
    let mid = Math.floor((first + last) / 2);
    if (arr[mid] === target) {
      return mid;
    } else if (arr[mid] < target) {
      last = mid - 1;
    } else {
      first = mid + 1;
    }
  }

  return -1;
}
```

The basic idea is to start with first = 0 and last = arr.length - 1 and to keep dividing the search space in half until we find the target value or until we've exhausted all possibilities. We can do this by keeping track of two indices: first and last. We start with first = 0 and last = arr.length - 1, which represents the range we're searching. We then calculate the midpoint of this range (first + last) / 2, which gives us the index we should check. If the element at this index (arr[mid]) is equal to the target value, then we've found it and we can return its index. If the element is less than the target value, then we know the target value must be in the right half of the array, so we can set last = mid - 1 (which represents the index of the last element in the left half of the array). If the element is greater than the target value, then we know the target value must be in the left half of the array, so we can set first = mid + 1 (which represents the index of the first element in the right half of the array). We then repeat this process, continuing to narrow down the search space until we find the target value or until we reach the end of the array.

If we reach the end of the array without finding the target value, then we return -1 to indicate that the target value was not found in the array.

This is a very efficient search algorithm because it only looks at O(log n) elements in the worst case, where n is the number of elements in the array. This is much faster than a linear search, which would require looking at every element in the array.

